● Use cases & users

  Researchers / journalists profiling a creator before writing about them — "what does this person actually believe, and has it shifted?" Today they'd skim 50 videos manually.

  Investors / recruiters doing due diligence on a founder, expert, or hire who has a public video presence. The chat answers "is this person consistent?" without watching hours of footage.

  Competitive analysis for content creators — point it at a rival channel to see themes, cadence, recurring references. Useful for podcasters, YouTubers, newsletter writers.

  Students / fans of a thinker (think Naval, Huberman, Lex) who want to query a body of work like a personal corpus. This is probably the most viral use case — "ask Naval anything" without RAG infra.

  PR / comms teams vetting someone before a partnership or appearance. "Has this person ever said anything about X?"

  Personal knowledge — anyone who's binge-watched a channel and wants to revisit ideas without scrubbing timestamps.

  Features beyond chat

  The chat is the headline, but on its own it's a demo. What turns this into something people open twice:

  1. Citations with timestamps. When the model says "the creator argued X in their 2023 video," link directly to the YouTube video at the right second. Without this, answers feel ungrounded — with it, the app becomes a research tool.
  Highest ROI feature you can add.
  2. Comparison mode. Two channels side-by-side, same questions answered against both. "How do Lex and Tim Ferriss differ on productivity?" This is the unique-to-this-app feature competitors can't easily ship.
  3. Evolution view. A timeline visualization of how a specific topic/opinion changed across videos. You already aggregate chronologically — surface the change explicitly. Pick a theme → see the slope.
  4. Saved questions / digests. Let users save a question and re-run it monthly as the creator posts new videos. Pairs with /schedule-style background runs. Turns a one-shot tool into a subscription.
  5. Export. Markdown/PDF of the profile + selected Q&A. Journalists and analysts need to paste this into their own docs.
  6. Quote extraction. "Pull the 10 strongest claims this person has ever made." Distinct from chat — it's a structured browse, not a conversation.
  7. Topic clustering / search inside the profile. Free-text search across summaries with filtering by theme/tone. Many users want to browse, not ask.

  The biggest gap in v1 is groundedness — chat without source links is hard to trust. Fix that first, then comparison mode is the differentiator.

